column42: The last known observation of a Morrison's Bumble Bee in the plan area was in 1922. This species has experienced considerable declines in recent years and has become increasingly rare across much of its range, despite significant efforts to find it {Xerces Society 2023}. In 2022, there were 920 bumble bee observations gathered from 106 surveys in South Dakota through the Great Plains Bumble Bee Atlas and Morrison's bumble bee was not detected  {Xerces Society 2023}. In Nebraska, the species has a Possibly Extirpated (SH) ranking, although two individuals were documented near Wildcat Hills State Recreation Area through the Nebraska Bumble Bee Atlas in 2023  {Bumble Bee Atlas 2024}. It is uncertain if this species still ocurrs in the plan area.

column42: The last known observation of this mason bee in the plan area was in 1983. This observation was from Toadstool Park on the Pine Ridge Ranger District in Nebraska. This species seems to have declined due unknown causes and has not been observed anywhere in Nebraska since the 1980s {NatureServe 2024}. It remains uncertain if this species still occurs in the plan area.

column42: The species (Parvindela terricola) is ranked as G5 with no state conservation ranks in either Nebraska or South Dakota. Only the subspecies (Parvindela terricola cinctipennis) has a conservation ranking of S1 in Nebraska to warrant consideration. The only record in the plan area is a research-grade Naturalist observation that is only identified to the species level (Parvindela terricola). One NENHP record of the subspecies from 1985 occurs on non-Forest Service lands within the administrative boundary, but not in FS-managed lands in the plan area. Therefore, it is uncertain if the subspecies occurs in the plan area, or just the species.
